explanation:
Given, $$f(x) = \left| {\matrix{
   {{x^3}} &amp; {\sin x} &amp; {\cos x}  \cr 
   6 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 
   p &amp; {{p^2}} &amp; {{p^3}}  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>where, p is a constant.<br><br>On differentiating both sides w.r.t. x, we get<br><br>$$f'(x) = \left| {\matrix{
   {3{x^2}} &amp; {\cos x} &amp; { - \sin x}  \cr 
   6 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 
   p &amp; {{p^2}} &amp; {{p^3}}  \cr 

 } } \right| + \left| {\matrix{
   {{x^3}} &amp; {\sin x} &amp; {\cos x}  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0  \cr 
   p &amp; {{p^2}} &amp; {{p^3}}  \cr 

 } } \right| + \left| {\matrix{
   {{x^3}} &amp; {\sin x} &amp; {\cos x}  \cr 
   6 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow f'(x) = \left| {\matrix{
   {3{x^2}} &amp; {\cos x} &amp; { - \sin x}  \cr 
   6 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 
   p &amp; {{p^2}} &amp; {{p^3}}  \cr 

 } } \right| + 0 + 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow f'(0) = \left| {\matrix{
   0 &amp; {\cos 0} &amp; { - \sin 0}  \cr 
   6 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 
   p &amp; {{p^2}} &amp; {{p^3}}  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow f'(0) = \left| {\matrix{
   0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0  \cr 
   6 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 
   p &amp; {{p^2}} &amp; {{p^3}}  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ = ( - 1)(6{p^3} - 0)$$<br><br>$$ =  - 6{p^3}$$

